{"kind":"article","hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/TUIkit\/documentation\/TUIkit"]]},"abstract":[{"text":"Understand the two-pass layout used by stacks and other layout containers.","type":"text"}],"metadata":{"roleHeading":"Article","role":"article","title":"Layout System","modules":[{"name":"TUIkit"}]},"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"type":"heading","text":"Overview","anchor":"Overview","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"TUIkit uses a two-pass layout system inspired by SwiftUI’s layout protocol. Layout containers like "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/TUIkit\/documentation\/TUIkit\/VStack","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/TUIkit\/documentation\/TUIkit\/HStack","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" first "},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"measure","type":"text"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","text":" each child, then "},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"render"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","text":" them with allocated sizes. This approach enables features like flexible spacers, proportional sizing, and proper alignment."}]},{"type":"heading","text":"The Two Passes","anchor":"The-Two-Passes","level":2},{"type":"heading","text":"Pass 1: Measure","anchor":"Pass-1-Measure","level":3},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The parent proposes a size to each child via ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"ProposedSize"},{"text":". Each child responds with a ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"ViewSize"},{"text":" that describes how much space it needs and whether it can flex.","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":null,"type":"codeListing","code":["Parent (VStack)","  ├─ propose(width: 40, height: nil) → Text    → ViewSize(10, 1, flexible: false)","  ├─ propose(width: 40, height: nil) → Spacer  → ViewSize(0, 0, flexible: true)","  └─ propose(width: 40, height: nil) → Button  → ViewSize(12, 1, flexible: false)"]},{"type":